---
import DefaultLayout from '@/layouts/DefaultLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---

<DefaultLayout
  title="Bad Credit Mortgage Renewal in Canada — Options & Strategies for 2026"
  description="Have bruised or bad credit? Learn your mortgage renewal options in Canada — from A-lenders to B-lenders to private lenders — and how to improve before renewal."
>
  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="container py-4 text-sm" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">
    <a href="/" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Home</a> › Bad Credit Mortgage Renewal
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="py-16 text-white" style="background: var(--primary)">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold mb-3 uppercase tracking-wide opacity-80">Updated March 2026 · 12-minute read</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-5 leading-tight">Bad Credit Mortgage Renewal in Canada — Options &amp; Strategies for 2026</h1>
      <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed opacity-90 mb-8">Your credit score has slipped. Your renewal date is approaching. You're wondering if you'll be able to keep your home. The good news: there are far more options than you likely realize, and the path forward is clearer than it feels right now.</p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
        <a href="/book-a-call" class="inline-block rounded-lg px-7 py-3 font-semibold text-sm" style="background: var(--secondary); color: white">
          Get a Free Strategy Call
        </a>
        <a href="#lender-tiers" class="inline-block rounded-lg px-7 py-3 font-semibold text-sm" style="border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.4); color: white">
          See Your Lender Options
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container max-w-4xl py-12">
    <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-10">
      <div class="flex-1">

        <div class="rounded-lg p-5 mb-8" style="background: var(--accent); border-left: 4px solid var(--secondary)">
          <p class="font-bold mb-2">You Are Not Alone</p>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">Hundreds of thousands of Canadians face mortgage renewal every year with credit challenges, income disruptions, or past financial difficulty. A bruised credit score does not automatically mean you lose your home — it means you need to understand which tier of lenders can work with your situation, and how to position your file.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">What Is "Bad Credit" in the Canadian Mortgage Context?</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">In the Canadian mortgage world, "credit score" refers to your Equifax or TransUnion score — a number from 300 to 900 that summarizes your credit history, payment behaviour, utilization, length of credit history, and types of credit. Mortgage lenders use this score, alongside income, property equity, and debt ratios, to assess the risk of lending to you.</p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">What constitutes "bad" or "bruised" credit for mortgages is more nuanced than for other consumer lending. Understanding which range you fall into determines which lender categories are available to you at renewal — and what rate premium you can expect to pay.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Credit Score Ranges and What They Mean at Renewal</h2>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr style="background: var(--primary); color: white">
                <th class="p-3 text-left">Score Range</th>
                <th class="p-3 text-left">Classification</th>
                <th class="p-3 text-left">Renewal Impact</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-bold">700+</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold" style="color: #16a34a">Excellent</td>
                <td class="p-3">Full access to all A-lenders — banks, monolines, credit unions. Best rates available. Straightforward renewal with any lender in Canada.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
                <td class="p-3 font-bold">660–699</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold" style="color: #65a30d">Good</td>
                <td class="p-3">Most A-lenders will approve. May face slightly higher rates or require more documentation. Some monolines set their floor at 680. Renewal is generally manageable.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-bold">620–659</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold" style="color: #d97706">Fair / Near-Prime</td>
                <td class="p-3">Many A-lenders decline. B-lenders become your primary option. Expect a rate premium of 0.5–1.5% over prime. Strong compensating factors (equity, stable income) become critical.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
                <td class="p-3 font-bold">580–619</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold" style="color: #ea580c">Poor / Sub-Prime</td>
                <td class="p-3">Firmly in B-lender territory. Rate premium of 1–2.5% over prime typical. Substantial equity (20%+ in the property) becomes essential to approval.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-bold">Below 580</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold" style="color: #dc2626">Damaged</td>
                <td class="p-3">B-lenders are difficult; private lenders become the primary option. Rates of 7–12%+ typical. Usually structured as a 1-year bridge while credit is actively rebuilt.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Why Renewal Is Different from a New Purchase</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">This is arguably the most important thing to understand if you're a homeowner with credit challenges: <strong>renewal is fundamentally easier than a new purchase for existing owners.</strong></p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">When you first took out your mortgage, you had to qualify from scratch — prove income, pass the stress test, provide a down payment, and clear a full underwriting review. At renewal, you are an existing homeowner with an established payment history, equity in the property, and a track record the lender can assess. Your current lender already holds security against the property and has seen how you've managed payments.</p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Your current lender has a strong incentive to keep renewing you as a customer, even if your credit has declined, provided you've kept mortgage payments current. Initiating power of sale proceedings is expensive, legally complex, time-consuming, and reputationally costly for lenders. In most cases, a lender would far rather offer renewal at a somewhat elevated rate than pursue enforcement.</p>

        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Additionally, since November 2024, straight transfer switches between federally regulated lenders no longer require the mortgage stress test — opening up more options for borrowers who need to change lenders at renewal without requalifying at inflated rates.</p>

        <h2 id="lender-tiers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">A-Lenders, B-Lenders, and Private Lenders Explained</h2>

        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The Canadian mortgage lending market is structured in three clear tiers. Understanding which tier applies to your situation is the foundation of any renewal strategy when credit is challenged.</p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr style="background: var(--primary); color: white">
                <th class="p-3 text-left">Feature</th>
                <th class="p-3 text-left">A-Lenders</th>
                <th class="p-3 text-left">B-Lenders</th>
                <th class="p-3 text-left">Private Lenders</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Typical credit score minimum</td>
                <td class="p-3">660+ (some 680+)</td>
                <td class="p-3">550–659</td>
                <td class="p-3">No minimum — equity-based</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Rate premium over prime</td>
                <td class="p-3">None — best rates</td>
                <td class="p-3">+0.50% to +2.50%</td>
                <td class="p-3">+3% to +8%+</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Max LTV</td>
                <td class="p-3">80% (uninsured) / 95% (insured)</td>
                <td class="p-3">Typically 80%</td>
                <td class="p-3">65–75% typically</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Typical lenders</td>
                <td class="p-3">Big 6 banks, First National, MCAP, Merix, RMG, Lendwise</td>
                <td class="p-3">Equitable Bank, Home Trust, Haventree, CMLS</td>
                <td class="p-3">Mortgage Investment Corps (MICs), individual investors</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Typical term length</td>
                <td class="p-3">1–5 years</td>
                <td class="p-3">1–2 years</td>
                <td class="p-3">6 months – 1 year</td>
              </tr>
              <tr style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
                <td class="p-3 font-medium">Access via</td>
                <td class="p-3">Bank directly or broker</td>
                <td class="p-3">Mortgage broker primarily</td>
                <td class="p-3">Mortgage broker only</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">B-Lenders in Canada: The Near-Prime Bridge</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">B-lenders occupy the crucial middle ground between mainstream banks and expensive private lenders. They are federally regulated, offer legitimate mortgage products at defined rates, and serve borrowers who don't quite meet A-lender criteria due to credit challenges, income documentation gaps, or recent financial events.</p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The goal for most borrowers who end up with a B-lender at renewal is strategic: spend one or two terms (typically 1–2 years each) actively rebuilding your credit profile, then graduate back to A-lender rates at the next renewal. Your mortgage broker should build this exit plan into your renewal strategy from the very beginning.</p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Major B-lenders active in the Canadian market as of 2026:</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">Equitable Bank</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Canada's Challenger Bank — a Schedule I federally regulated bank with a strong alternative mortgage line. Accepts bruised credit with compensating equity and income. Broker channel only.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">Home Trust</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">One of Canada's oldest and largest alternative lenders. Offers multiple credit-challenged tiers (Accelerator, Classic). Broad flexibility for near-prime and self-employed borrowers.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">Haventree Bank</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Focused alternative mortgage lender known for competitive B-space pricing. Solid option for borrowers with stable employment income but credit blemishes from past events.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">MCAP (Fusion / Eclipse)</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">MCAP's alternative product lines serve near-prime borrowers. Particularly strong for self-employed clients and those with non-traditional income structures alongside credit challenges.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">First National (Excalibur)</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Canada's largest non-bank lender also has Excalibur, its near-prime product. Known for fair pricing and strong broker relationships. Good for files with solid equity backing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--primary)">Merix Financial</p>
            <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Competitive broker-channel lender with near-prime offerings. Good pricing within the B-space for well-positioned files with meaningful equity and stable income.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">All B-lenders are accessible only through a licensed mortgage broker. A broker will know which specific B-lender is most likely to approve your file given your credit profile, income type, LTV, and property location — and will position your application to maximize approval chances.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">5 Steps to Improve Your Credit Before Renewal</h2>

        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">If you have time before your renewal date — even 6 to 12 months — there are concrete, measurable steps that can move your score meaningfully upward and potentially shift you into a better lending tier.</p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <div class="rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0 text-white" style="background: var(--secondary)">1</div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold mb-1">Never miss a payment — on anything</p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Payment history accounts for roughly 35% of your credit score — the single largest factor. Set up automatic minimum payments on every credit product you hold, without exception. One missed payment can drop your score by 50–100 points. Most critically: keep your existing mortgage payments immaculate. A clean mortgage payment record is your strongest asset at renewal.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <div class="rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0 text-white" style="background: var(--secondary)">2</div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold mb-1">Reduce credit utilization below 30%</p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Credit utilization — the percentage of your available credit limit you're currently using — is the second-largest scoring factor (roughly 30%). If you have a $10,000 limit and carry a $7,000 balance, you're at 70% utilization — damaging to your score. Pay balances down to below 30% on each card, ideally below 10% if possible. This is often the fastest way to lift a score by 30–80 points.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <div class="rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0 text-white" style="background: var(--secondary)">3</div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold mb-1">Check your credit report for errors and dispute them</p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Canadian consumers can request a free credit report from both Equifax and TransUnion. Errors — duplicate accounts, incorrectly reported late payments, accounts belonging to someone else — are more common than most people expect. Dispute errors directly with the bureau in writing. Correcting a significant error can improve your score by 30–100+ points, sometimes very quickly.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <div class="rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0 text-white" style="background: var(--secondary)">4</div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold mb-1">Avoid applying for new credit in the 6–12 months before renewal</p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Every credit application generates a "hard inquiry" that temporarily lowers your score by 5–10 points. New credit also shortens your average account age. In the 6–12 months before your renewal, avoid applications for car loans, new credit cards, lines of credit, or any new borrowing. Hold off until after your renewal is secured.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <div class="rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold flex-shrink-0 text-white" style="background: var(--secondary)">5</div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold mb-1">Address collections and judgments strategically — not impulsively</p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">If you have accounts in collections or court judgments on your file, lenders often require resolution before approving a renewal. However, paying an old collection doesn't immediately remove it — it remains as a "paid collection" for years. Talk to your mortgage broker before paying off old collections; the timing, approach, and negotiation with collectors can materially affect how it impacts your score and your renewal file.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Can I Port My Mortgage If I Have Bad Credit?</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Mortgage porting — transferring your existing mortgage to a new property when you move — is a different mechanism from renewal, and it can be advantageous for borrowers with credit challenges. When you port a mortgage, you retain your current interest rate and terms on the existing balance. Because you're not applying for an entirely new mortgage, many lenders apply less stringent credit scrutiny at the time of porting.</p>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The key advantage: if you locked in a low rate years ago, porting lets you carry that rate to your new property even if your credit has since declined and you wouldn't qualify for a new mortgage at today's rates. The ported balance rides under the existing terms; only the "top-up" portion (any additional borrowing above the existing balance) would be subject to full current qualification requirements.</p>

        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Porting timelines and mechanics vary significantly by lender — most allow 30 to 90 days between the sale of your current home and the purchase of the new one. Speak to a mortgage broker about your specific lender's porting terms well in advance if you are considering moving.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">What Documents Do Lenders Want to See?</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">When renewing with credit challenges, lenders — especially B-lenders — scrutinize your file more carefully than in a standard renewal. A thorough, organized document package signals that you are a serious, responsible borrower and can make the difference between approval and decline. Have these ready before your broker submits your file.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold mb-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--secondary)">Income Verification</p>
            <ul class="text-sm space-y-1" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">
              <li>• Last 2 years of T4 slips</li>
              <li>• 2 most recent pay stubs (employed)</li>
              <li>• 2 years T1 General NOAs (self-employed)</li>
              <li>• Employment letter confirming status and income</li>
              <li>• 3–6 months of bank statements showing deposits</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold mb-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--secondary)">Mortgage &amp; Property</p>
            <ul class="text-sm space-y-1" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">
              <li>• Most recent mortgage statement</li>
              <li>• Full mortgage payment history (12–24 months)</li>
              <li>• Current property tax statement</li>
              <li>• Property insurance certificate</li>
              <li>• Appraisal (typically required by B-lenders)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold mb-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--secondary)">Credit &amp; Identity</p>
            <ul class="text-sm space-y-1" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">
              <li>• Valid government-issued photo ID</li>
              <li>• SIN (for credit bureau authorization)</li>
              <li>• Letters of explanation for credit events</li>
              <li>• Proof of resolved collections (if applicable)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
            <p class="font-bold mb-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--secondary)">Compensating Factors</p>
            <ul class="text-sm space-y-1" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">
              <li>• Evidence of substantial equity (low LTV)</li>
              <li>• Recent savings account statements</li>
              <li>• Evidence of improved or stable income</li>
              <li>• Letter explaining past credit events (job loss, illness, separation)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Related guides -->
        <div class="mt-12 border-t pt-8" style="border-color: var(--border)">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Related Guides</h2>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <a href="/mortgage-renewal-bad-credit-financial-difficulty" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Renewal With Financial Difficulty</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Denial risk, Canadian Mortgage Charter rights, and the full lender tier pathway.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="/mortgage-lender-types-canada" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Canadian Lender Types Compared</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Banks, monolines, credit unions, B-lenders, private — full comparison.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="/mortgage-broker-renewal" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Using a Mortgage Broker at Renewal</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Free access to 30+ lenders including B-lenders you cannot reach directly.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="/switching-lenders-at-renewal" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Switching Lenders at Renewal</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">No stress test for straight switches since 2024. The full 8-step process.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="/self-employed-mortgage-renewal" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Self-Employed Mortgage Renewal</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Income documentation challenges often accompany credit challenges for business owners.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="/mortgage-renewal-guide" class="rounded-lg p-4" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
              <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--primary)">Complete Mortgage Renewal Guide</p>
              <p class="text-xs" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Everything you need to know about renewing your Canadian mortgage in 2026.</p>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Sidebar -->
      <aside class="w-full lg:w-64 flex-shrink-0">
        <div class="sticky top-6 space-y-6">
          <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="background: var(--accent); border: 1px solid var(--border)">
            <h3 class="font-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--primary)">On This Page</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">What Is Bad Credit?</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">Credit Score Ranges</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">Why Renewal Is Easier</a></li>
              <li><a href="#lender-tiers" style="color: var(--secondary)">A, B &amp; Private Lenders</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">B-Lenders in Canada</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">5 Steps to Improve Credit</a></li>
              <li><a href="#" style="color: var(--secondary)">Porting With Bad Credit</a></li>
